<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910613-0035</DOCNO><DOCID>910613-0035.</DOCID><HL>   Developer Is Indicted   For Alleged Payments   To Ex-Hud Official</HL><DATE>06/13/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><GV>HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT (HUD)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>FLORIDA (FL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- A federal grand jury in West Palm Beach,Fla., charged that a Texas-based real estate developer paidbribes to a senior official of the Department of Housing andUrban Development in connection with three urban-developmentprojects.   The grand jury returned two indictments charging the FortWorth developer, Leonard Briscoe, with 23 counts of bribery,fraud and conspiracy. It also charged Maurice David Steier,an Omaha, Neb., lawyer, as a participant in the allegedbribery of Dubois Gilliam, who was a deputy assistantsecretary at HUD from 1984 to 1987.</LP><TEXT>   The grand jury said the scheme involved HUD's funding ofthree Briscoe-developed projects in Palm Beach County, Fla.   Mr. Briscoe said in a statement that he was innocent andlooked forward &quot;to the opportunity to clear my name.&quot; Mr.Steier was reported out of his Omaha office when a reportertelephoned; his office said he wasn't expected to comment.   In an unrelated criminal case, Mr. Gilliam pleaded guiltyin 1989 to receiving an unlawful gratuity and to conspiracyto defraud the U.S. He served an 18-month prison term.   Mr. Gilliam cooperated with the Florida investigation. Healso was an important witness for a House committee thatprobed the HUD influence-peddling scandal that emerged in1989, and is cooperating with the HUD special prosecutor,Arlin Adams.</TEXT></DOC>